<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>



<section xml:id="lesson4_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Lingering Effects</title>

<p> You might be thinking that the previous limitation was not *too* bad.
All we need to do to measure the state is to perform 1000 consecutive 
measurements, and that will extract approximate probabilities of each outcome.
Unfortunately, there is a second limitation of quantum measurement.</p>

<sidebyside widths="80% 20%" valign="top">
    <p>
    <p> Consider measuring the temperature of a cup of hot chocolate.</p>  
    <ul>
        <li><term>Question:</term> What is the temperature of the hot chocolate?</li>
        <li><term>Device:</term> A thermometer</li>
        <li><term>Method:</term> Place the thermometer in the hot chocolate and read the value.</li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    <image source="hotchocolate_COLOR.png" width="50%" />
<!--    <image source="hotchocolate.png" width="66%" />-->
  </sidebyside>
  <p>What would happen if we chose a different measurement device and method?</p>
  <p>  
  Instead, let's imagine measuring the temperature of a cup of hot chocolate by timing how long 
  it takes for the hot chocolate to melt an ice cube.
    <ul>
        <li><term>Question:</term> What is the temperature of the hot chocolate?</li>
        <li><term>Device:</term> A stopwatch</li>
        <li><term>Method:</term> Place an ice cube in the hot chocolate and time how long it takes to melt.</li>
    </ul>
</p>

<!--<p><alert><insert>JEN - Put in a checkpoint question asking what the effect would be of this measurement method</insert></alert></p>-->

  <exercise label="L4_3 Measurement Effect">
    <title>Effects of Measurement</title>
    <idx>L4_3 Measurement Effect</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the effect of this measurement method?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>The temperature of the hot cocoa decreases.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>There is no effect.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>The temperature of the hot cocoa increases.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Think about how this measurement method differs from the original method (using a thermometer).</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

    <p> This is a very different measurement device and method, but it can still give us information 
    about the temperature of the hot chocolate. Is there any downside to this method? Does someone still want to 
    drink the hot chocolate after the ice cube has cooled it down?
    </p>






<p><insert>In quantum systems, the measurement changes the state of the measured qubit.</insert> More specifically,
if the qubit is in superposition, then the measurement will cause it to lose its superposition, and it will 
hold the same value as the measured outcome. </p>



<p>If we were to consider what this would mean in python, it would
look like the following for the code on the top and two different runs of the code on the bottom: </p>

<!--<sidebyside widths="50% 25% 25%" valign="top">
    
    <image source="4_3_python1.png" width="66%" />
    <image source="4_3_pyoutput_1.png" width="66%" />
    <image source="4_3_pyoutput_2.png" width="66%" />
  </sidebyside>-->

  <image source="4_3_python1.png" width="70%" />
  <sidebyside widths="15% 35% 35% 15%" valign="top">
    <p> </p>
    <image source="4_3_pyoutput_1.png" width="66%" />
    <image source="4_3_pyoutput_2.png" width="66%" />
    <p> </p>
  </sidebyside>

  <p> Once we print out the variable the first time, every subsequent print statement will print out the same think
  unless more operations are performed on the variable to place it back into superposition.</p>



<p> We can also apply this to our one qubit system with H gates. Now we have a much more complete
picture of what was happening:</p>
<p>  <image source="L4.3-H-gate-state-output.png" width="66%" /> </p>


<p> To really challenge our understanding at this point, let's consider the following circuit and use 
it to answer the following questions:</p>

<p>  <image source="L4.3-measure-in-h-gate-BLACK-labelled.png" width="75%" /> </p>
<!--<p><insert>Swap out this picture to have only one of the choices - starting with black ball, just for kicks</insert></p>-->

<!--
<p><insert> Checkpoint 1: 
<ul>
<li>Black ball only</li>
<li>White ball only</li>
<li> 50% chance of black ball and 50% chance of white ball only (but not in superposition)</li>
<li> 50/50 superposition of black and white balls, positive phase</li>
<li> 50/50 superposition of black and white balls, negative phase (answer)</li>
</ul>
</insert></p>
-->

  <exercise label="L4_3 Calculate State A">
    <title>Calculate State at A</title>
    <idx>L4_3 Calculate_A</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>Describe the state the qubit at A (after the first H gate but before the measurement).</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>Black ball only </p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_A.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>White ball only</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_B.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>50% chance of white ball and 50% chance of black ball (but not in superposition)</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_C.png" width="50%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>50/50 superposition of white and black balls, positive phase</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_D.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
            <p>50/50 superposition of white and black balls, negative phase</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_E.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

<!--
<p><insert> Checkpoint 2: Describe the state of the qubit after the first measurement
<ul><li>Black ball only</li>
<li>White ball only</li>
<li> 50% chance of black ball and 50% chance of white ball only (but not in superposition) (answer)</li>
<li> 50/50 superposition of black and white balls, positive phase</li>
<li> 50/50 superposition of black and white balls, negative phase</li>
<li> 50/50 superposition of black and white balls, phase unknown </li>
</ul>
</insert></p>
-->

  <exercise label="L4_3 Calculate State B">
    <title>Calculate State at B</title>
    <idx>L4_3_Calculate_B</idx>
    <statement>
      <p>Describe the state the qubit at B (after the first measurement).</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>Black ball only </p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_A.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>White ball only</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_B.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>
            <p>50% chance of white ball and 50% chance of black ball (but not in superposition)</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_C.png" width="50%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct!!</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>50/50 superposition of white and black balls, positive phase</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_D.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>50/50 superposition of white and black balls, negative phase</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_E.png" width="25%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement>
            <p>50/50 superposition of white and black balls, unknown phase</p>
            <image source="L4_3_2_F.png" width="35%" />
        </statement>
        <feedback><p> </p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <hint>
      <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p> 
    </hint>
  </exercise>

